{\"video_title\": \"Tail Generation Pattern | Coursera\", \"transcript\": \"вЂ‹When we're having a long conversation вЂ‹with a large language model, вЂ‹sometimes we'll run into the challenge that вЂ‹the large language model will вЂ‹forget the rules of the game. вЂ‹It'll forget what we're trying to accomplish. вЂ‹What is the task that we're working on? вЂ‹One of the things we need is a way to remind вЂ‹the large language model, what are we doing? вЂ‹We'd like it to remind itself if possible. вЂ‹The way that we can do that is by using what вЂ‹we call the tail generation pattern. вЂ‹The idea behind this is that we're going вЂ‹to generate a tail, вЂ‹an end to the output that вЂ‹the large language model produces вЂ‹that will help remind it what we're doing. вЂ‹The tail is going to always be вЂ‹generated at the end of its output. вЂ‹The tail will remind вЂ‹the large language model what the rules of the game are. вЂ‹We're going to see this in the context of вЂ‹combining the tail pattern вЂ‹with the alternative approaches pattern вЂ‹and with the ask-for-input pattern. вЂ‹We're going to put all these things together and вЂ‹we're going to see how this is a really useful thing. вЂ‹Generating a tail on our conversation using вЂ‹a tail generation pattern is really вЂ‹effective in maintaining our conversation вЂ‹longer and maintaining the rules вЂ‹and the knowledge of our rules longer. вЂ‹I've actually used this several вЂ‹times and I haven't talked about it, вЂ‹but I'm going to show you what it does. вЂ‹This is the prompt that I used in вЂ‹the alternative approaches pattern discussion. вЂ‹I'm asking ChatGPT to вЂ‹generate a set of prompts to solve a particular task. вЂ‹I'm asking ChatGPT to help us with prompt engineering. вЂ‹I'm going to give it a task and it's going вЂ‹to generate possible prompts вЂ‹that we could use to perform that task with ChatGPT. вЂ‹Now, if I do this over and over, вЂ‹what's going to happen is eventually ChatGPT вЂ‹will probably forget what we're trying to do. вЂ‹The reason this is important is because we're вЂ‹using several different rules and patterns in our prompt. вЂ‹In our original prompt, we use the alternative вЂ‹approaches pattern and we use the ask-for-input pattern. вЂ‹As we go further down in the conversation, вЂ‹one of the risks is that it forgets one of those rules. вЂ‹For example, it might forget to give вЂ‹us alternative approaches and just give us one. вЂ‹Or it might forget to ask for input. вЂ‹What we do is at the end of the prompt, вЂ‹we include a new set of instructions. вЂ‹We say, 'From now on, at the end of every output, вЂ‹repeat the rules of the game to me.' вЂ‹And then we list out what the rules are. вЂ‹In this case, the rules were: вЂ‹provide alternative approaches and ask for input. вЂ‹What's going to happen is every time вЂ‹ChatGPT provides an output, вЂ‹at the very end of that output, вЂ‹it's going to repeat those rules. вЂ‹By repeating those rules, it's actually providing вЂ‹a prompt back to itself in the conversation history. вЂ‹Remember, the way these models work is they're looking вЂ‹at the entire history of the conversation to вЂ‹decide what the next word should be. вЂ‹By having the rules repeated at the end of every output, вЂ‹the rules are always present in the most recent history. вЂ‹This makes it much more likely that the model вЂ‹will continue to follow those rules correctly. вЂ‹This is why we call it the tail generation pattern. вЂ‹We're generating a tail at the end of the output вЂ‹that reinforces the instructions and rules. вЂ‹It's a way of providing self-reminders to the model. вЂ‹This is particularly useful when you have very вЂ‹long, complex prompts with many different instructions. вЂ‹It helps maintain the state and the behavior вЂ‹of the model over a long interaction. вЂ‹It's a simple but very powerful technique вЂ‹for keeping your prompt engineering effective вЂ‹throughout a long session with a large language model. вЂ‹So that's the tail generation pattern. вЂ‹It's about having the model generate a summary вЂ‹or a reminder of its instructions at the end вЂ‹of its own output to keep it on track.\"}